  "A function divided by another function": "",
  "Two functions added together": "",
  "A function applied to the output of another function, written as f(g(x))": "",
  "A composite function is formed when one function is applied to the result of another, written as (f o g)(x) = f(g(x)). The chain rule is specifically designed for differentiating composite functions.": "",
  "What does 'inner function' mean in the context of the chain rule?": "",
  "The function that is applied first (the input to the outer function)": "",
  "The function that is applied last": "",
  "The derivative of the composite function": "",
  "The constant term in the expression": "",
  "In f(g(x)), the inner function is g(x) -- it is evaluated first, and its output becomes the input to the outer function f. When applying the chain rule, you must also multiply by g'(x).": "",
  "What does the mnemonic 'lo d-hi minus hi d-lo over lo-lo' refer to?": "",
  "The chain rule": "",
  "The quotient rule": "",
  "The power rule": "",
  "The product rule": "",
  "This mnemonic helps remember the quotient rule: (g * f' - f * g')/g^2, where 'lo' is the denominator g, 'hi' is the numerator f, 'd-hi' means derivative of f, and 'd-lo' means derivative of g.": "",
  "What does 'outer function' mean in the context of the chain rule?": "",
  "The function applied last (that wraps around the inner function)": "",
  "The function that appears on the x-axis": "",
  "The function applied first in a composition": "",
  "Any function that is not a polynomial": "",
  "In f(g(x)), the outer function is f -- it is applied to the result of g(x). When using the chain rule, you first differentiate the outer function while keeping the inner function unchanged, then multiply by the derivative of the inner function.": "",
